The propyl group is larger than the ethyl group and will increase the molecular weight and size, leading to higher London dispersion forces. However, tripropylamine has three propyl groups instead of an ethyl and two hydrogens in ethylamine. Each additional propyl group increases the melting point. A single propyl group versus an ethyl group is estimated to increase the melting point by about +4 degrees Celsius. Since there are two additional propyl groups in tripropylamine as compared to ethylamine, the total estimated increase would be +4 * 2 = +8 degrees Celsius.
